WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.086 --> 00:00:06.816
Brothers and sisters, in today’s
Gospel we heard about the blind man

00:00:06.816 --> 00:00:12.069
Bartimaeus, sitting by the roadside, who
caught sight of—really, who heard—Jesus

00:00:12.069 --> 00:00:15.412
passing by as He was leaving Jericho.

00:00:15.412 --> 00:00:18.755
Jericho, in translation—erm—in
Hebrew, means “moon”, which

00:00:18.755 --> 00:00:20.187
also suggests darkness.

00:00:20.187 --> 00:00:28.306
And of course you know that parable, that
on the road to Jericho they beat up the

00:00:28.306 --> 00:00:35.947
man who was going down, and the Samaritan
came to him; and Jericho was marked out

00:00:35.947 --> 00:00:40.245
as a city of darkness, a city of evil.

00:00:41.726 --> 00:00:49.755
And it’s right there, in that city, that
the blind man is sitting by the roadside.

00:00:49.755 --> 00:00:53.769
In the Bible, sitting
points to two attitudes.

00:00:53.769 --> 00:00:59.791
It can mean listening, but then
it’s always said that someone got

00:00:59.791 --> 00:01:05.311
up afterwards; teaching, on the
other hand, was done sitting down.

00:01:05.311 --> 00:01:10.329
Yet it can also point to
resurrection, when someone rises,

00:01:10.329 --> 00:01:13.842
and it can also point to death.

00:01:13.842 --> 00:01:19.864
And you see, for anyone to reach
Jerusalem, they had to come

00:01:19.864 --> 00:01:25.886
out of Jericho, out of the city
of darkness, and pass through.

00:01:26.866 --> 00:01:34.044
And that blind man, Bartimaeus, has been
sitting there perhaps for years, and the

00:01:34.044 --> 00:01:37.633
Bible tells us his father’s name exactly.

00:01:37.633 --> 00:01:43.786
And we see something interesting
here: he is sitting by the roadside.

00:01:43.786 --> 00:01:45.837
Is Bartimaeus a believer?

00:01:45.837 --> 00:01:53.529
Remember that parable where it speaks of
the sower of God’s word: “The seed that

00:01:53.529 --> 00:02:02.246
was thrown by the path did not bear much
fruit.” So, Bartimaeus is not on the path.

00:02:03.366 --> 00:02:09.278
He’s sitting by the road, but
he’s not on the road in the

00:02:09.278 --> 00:02:12.007
sense of moving forward in faith.

00:02:12.007 --> 00:02:19.739
And today we can see and learn four things
that can help us in our spiritual life.

00:02:19.739 --> 00:02:24.742
Bartimaeus may have been physically
blind, but perhaps many of us

00:02:24.742 --> 00:02:26.561
here are spiritually blind.

00:02:26.561 --> 00:02:33.383
And the first thing we can learn is that
when Bartimaeus heard that Jesus was

00:02:33.383 --> 00:02:40.206
passing by, he began to shout, calling
on the name of Jesus to have mercy.

00:02:41.326 --> 00:02:46.154
And we see that the whole
crowd is trying to silence him.

00:02:46.154 --> 00:02:49.373
I don’t know why they were silencing him.

00:02:49.373 --> 00:02:54.201
Maybe so he wouldn’t embarrass them;
maybe because they thought he wasn’t

00:02:54.201 --> 00:02:56.615
worthy, that he didn’t deserve Jesus.

00:02:56.615 --> 00:02:59.431
Maybe they thought he wasn’t a believer.

00:02:59.431 --> 00:03:06.674
I don’t know, but the Gospel says they all
tried to shut him up so he wouldn’t shout.

00:03:06.674 --> 00:03:11.905
Just think for a moment how, we believers
today, are sometimes pinned down.

00:03:12.945 --> 00:03:19.005
We sit there, not moving, spiritually
blind, and all of it is suffocating

00:03:19.005 --> 00:03:25.066
us, just as they tried to discourage
Bartimaeus from going, so he wouldn’t

00:03:25.066 --> 00:03:27.863
be heard, so he wouldn’t shout.

00:03:27.863 --> 00:03:34.857
Many of us today are sitting like that;
we haven’t even the strength to shout,

00:03:34.857 --> 00:03:39.985
we haven’t the strength to cry out,
because we’ve been discouraged—maybe

00:03:39.985 --> 00:03:45.113
by certain examples, maybe by our
own life, maybe by circumstances—but

00:03:45.113 --> 00:03:47.445
something is constantly choking us.

00:03:48.245 --> 00:03:53.051
Something is always stopping us
from coming to Jesus, and we can all

00:03:53.051 --> 00:03:57.857
often see it in our lives: there’s
always something that crops up to

00:03:57.857 --> 00:04:02.663
stand between us and Jesus, so that
sometimes you don’t even have the

00:04:02.663 --> 00:04:05.620
strength to shout out and go to Him.

00:04:05.620 --> 00:04:09.687
But he pulled himself together,
gathered his strength, and cried out.

00:04:09.687 --> 00:04:12.645
And the Gospel says that he leapt up.

00:04:15.446 --> 00:04:20.933
I’m asking a question of all of us:
when are we going to leap up—when

00:04:20.933 --> 00:04:25.689
are we going to shake ourselves
out of our comfort, out of our

00:04:25.689 --> 00:04:30.446
lukewarmness—when are we going to break
free from our fears, from our doubts?

00:04:31.606 --> 00:04:37.777
You see, we can learn a lot from
this: precisely when things are hard,

00:04:37.777 --> 00:04:44.830
precisely when it’s hardest for you, you
need to cry out, you need to cry out.

00:04:44.830 --> 00:04:51.442
A similar prayer to the one he was
saying was taken up in the Eastern

00:04:51.442 --> 00:04:56.290
Churches on their prayer beads,
praying with a similar phrase: “Jesus,

00:04:56.290 --> 00:05:02.021
Son of David, have mercy on me,”
and it’s simply repeated like that.

00:05:02.021 --> 00:05:09.074
We, our Church has the rosary, but you
see we have ways, when it’s hard, when

00:05:09.074 --> 00:05:15.686
you’re pinned down, when you can’t get
up, to shout, to cry out, to plead.

00:05:16.506 --> 00:05:20.307
And it’s precisely in those moments
that a person mustn’t lose heart.

00:05:20.307 --> 00:05:25.376
You need to be strong enough to cry
out from the very depths of your heart.

00:05:25.376 --> 00:05:26.960
And God hears that prayer.

00:05:26.960 --> 00:05:31.711
When people ask what a powerful prayer
is, it’s the one that comes from the

00:05:31.711 --> 00:05:36.146
depths of your heart, the one that
rises from the cry of your soul.

00:05:36.146 --> 00:05:38.681
Imagine how a blind man must have felt.

00:05:38.681 --> 00:05:40.582
He had nothing left to lose.

00:05:40.582 --> 00:05:42.166
Jesus was his last chance.

00:05:42.826 --> 00:05:44.663
Jesus was his last remedy.

00:05:44.663 --> 00:05:49.809
Maybe you too have come to the
edge, where you think there’s no one

00:05:49.809 --> 00:05:52.749
left, no one you can truly turn to.

00:05:52.749 --> 00:05:56.792
Let’s be realistic, people: we all
end up disappointing one another.

00:05:56.792 --> 00:06:01.202
Today we swear by love and friendship,
and then a year later—three,

00:06:01.202 --> 00:06:02.305
five—everything falls apart.

00:06:02.305 --> 00:06:03.408
There’s nothing anywhere.

00:06:03.408 --> 00:06:08.186
All of us experience being pinned
down, but we mustn’t stay that way.

00:06:09.186 --> 00:06:16.383
So today, here, we learn from Bartimaeus:
when others try to silence you, when

00:06:16.383 --> 00:06:23.067
others put pressure on you, or when
you’ve allowed something yourself to pin

00:06:23.067 --> 00:06:30.264
you to the ground—shout, shout, “Jesus,
Son of David, have mercy on me.” Look,

00:06:30.264 --> 00:06:33.863
here’s the second thing we can learn.

00:06:33.863 --> 00:06:37.976
He jumped up and threw off his cloak.

00:06:37.976 --> 00:06:44.146
That cloak was everything he had:
his security, his bed, his home.

00:06:45.906 --> 00:06:48.843
That cloak meant everything to him.

00:06:48.843 --> 00:06:55.208
But when he heard that Jesus
was passing by, so that he could

00:06:55.208 --> 00:06:58.146
move, he threw that cloak off.

00:07:00.957 --> 00:07:06.848
When will we be ready to throw
off the cloak of false beliefs,

00:07:06.848 --> 00:07:13.191
the cloak of sin that holds us
back, the cloak of fear and doubt?

00:07:13.191 --> 00:07:15.910
When will we take it off?

00:07:15.910 --> 00:07:20.894
That’s why we can’t draw near to
Jesus, because spiritually we’re

00:07:20.894 --> 00:07:27.238
constantly wearing some kind of cloak
that we don’t want to let go of.

00:07:28.318 --> 00:07:32.335
This is such a wonderful example today,
because when we remember that rich young

00:07:32.335 --> 00:07:36.639
man, there’s that story where the rich
young man comes to Jesus and says, “Lord,

00:07:36.639 --> 00:07:41.804
what must I do to enter the Kingdom of
Heaven?” And then he lists it all: I do

00:07:41.804 --> 00:07:45.534
this, I do this, I do this — everything’s
great, according to the commandments.

00:07:45.534 --> 00:07:48.978
And then Jesus says to him, “You’re
only missing one more thing.”

00:07:49.438 --> 00:07:54.348
“Go and sell what you have.” And
he was rich. But you see, the

00:07:54.348 --> 00:07:58.908
problem in his heart wasn’t wealth
itself, it was his attachment to it.

00:07:58.908 --> 00:08:04.169
And the Gospel ends by saying that the
young man went away from Jesus sad.

00:08:04.169 --> 00:08:08.378
Yet here we see Bartimaeus: his only
treasure, his security, that one

00:08:08.378 --> 00:08:11.184
cloak—he takes it off and throws it away.

00:08:11.184 --> 00:08:16.445
So now let’s think about us believers
today: how often do we say we believe

00:08:16.445 --> 00:08:22.058
in God, and yet there are certain things
we simply don’t want to let go of.

00:08:23.238 --> 00:08:25.750
We think we can’t live without sin.

00:08:25.750 --> 00:08:28.262
We don’t want to cast it off.

00:08:28.262 --> 00:08:31.492
We cling to security, career,
selfishness, appearance—whatever you like.

00:08:31.492 --> 00:08:37.235
How many of these cloaks do we all have,
saying we’re believers, yet we don’t take

00:08:37.235 --> 00:08:40.465
them off, we don’t want to let them go.

00:08:40.465 --> 00:08:42.977
We feel safer wrapped up in them.

00:08:42.977 --> 00:08:47.643
And yet God’s word calls us to
this, and so does the example

00:08:47.643 --> 00:08:49.438
of this blind man, Bartimaeus.

00:08:50.178 --> 00:08:54.774
Cast off everything that holds
you back from coming to Jesus.

00:08:54.774 --> 00:08:59.370
Cast off everything that gives
you a false sense of security.

00:08:59.370 --> 00:09:03.966
Here the Lord wants to teach
us trust — trust in him.

00:09:03.966 --> 00:09:08.144
If you are seeking me, you
leave everything else behind.

00:09:08.144 --> 00:09:13.158
And that is the story of every
saint, every apostle, every believer.

00:09:13.158 --> 00:09:16.919
Either Jesus is in first
place, or he isn’t.

00:09:16.919 --> 00:09:22.351
And then tonight we can reflect:
what is my cloak — the one I

00:09:22.351 --> 00:09:24.858
no longer want to take off?

00:09:27.649 --> 00:09:34.301
The third thing we can learn from
this blind man: he is blind, and the

00:09:34.301 --> 00:09:37.405
Gospel says he wasn’t blind from birth.

00:09:37.405 --> 00:09:39.179
He’s blind, he’s ill.

00:09:39.179 --> 00:09:44.501
Imagine what it’s like to be like
that, alone, seeing nothing, sitting

00:09:44.501 --> 00:09:47.162
by the roadside, people mocking you.

00:09:47.162 --> 00:09:52.483
And at first the man thought—when
he tore himself away, sprang up,

00:09:52.483 --> 00:09:58.249
threw all that off, and came before
Jesus—what did he say to him?

00:09:59.949 --> 00:10:02.340
It’s not like the way we pray, is it?

00:10:02.340 --> 00:10:05.529
“Give me this, give me that,
give me this, give me that.”

00:10:08.901 --> 00:10:15.173
And the third thing we need to learn
from Bartimaeus: what did he call Jesus?

00:10:15.173 --> 00:10:20.191
“Teacher, Teacher.” The third thing
we need to learn about our attitude

00:10:20.191 --> 00:10:25.628
before God: he didn’t come and say,
“Jesus, please, quickly touch my eyes

00:10:25.628 --> 00:10:30.646
so I can see,” but he addressed him:
“Teacher.” Mary Magdalene addressed

00:10:30.646 --> 00:10:36.501
Jesus with the very same word as
well, even though she was a sinner.

00:10:37.321 --> 00:10:41.141
Jesus – she was blind in the sense that
she didn’t recognise the risen Jesus

00:10:41.141 --> 00:10:44.962
until he spoke to her, and then she
said the very same word: “Teacher.”

00:10:47.529 --> 00:10:51.778
And she was spiritually blind,
so she didn’t recognise Jesus.

00:10:51.778 --> 00:10:56.877
But what’s crucial, both with Mary
Magdalene and with Bartimaeus, is that

00:10:56.877 --> 00:10:59.852
they take the stance of a disciple.

00:10:59.852 --> 00:11:02.827
They take the stance of a disciple.

00:11:02.827 --> 00:11:05.802
They don’t immediately
push their own agenda.

00:11:07.122 --> 00:11:13.237
We, we often come before God as if
he’s a jukebox: give me this, give

00:11:13.237 --> 00:11:15.683
me that, fulfil this, fulfil that.

00:11:15.683 --> 00:11:19.352
Can I really say I’m a disciple of Jesus?

00:11:19.352 --> 00:11:21.798
Do I let Jesus shape me?

00:11:21.798 --> 00:11:28.322
Do I let him teach me, and do I walk
after Jesus if I’m his disciple?

00:11:28.322 --> 00:11:33.622
Half of us would come just to
take something from him, for him

00:11:33.622 --> 00:11:38.922
to do something for us, but we
wouldn’t want to be his disciples.

00:11:40.422 --> 00:11:46.332
And to be a true disciple of God means
coming before God with that attitude:

00:11:46.332 --> 00:11:53.424
that you turn to him first out of love,
and God will add all the rest to you.

00:11:53.424 --> 00:11:58.941
That’s why the third thing we should
learn, every time we come into God’s

00:11:58.941 --> 00:12:04.063
presence, is to take the posture of a
disciple: “Speak, Teacher.” Because each

00:12:04.063 --> 00:12:08.397
time the Teacher answered Mary Magdalene,
Bartimaeus, and everyone in Holy

00:12:08.397 --> 00:12:10.762
Scripture: “Your faith has saved you.”

00:12:11.782 --> 00:12:16.207
Because for Jesus, neither Mary
Magdalene’s sins nor Bartimaeus’

00:12:16.207 --> 00:12:23.583
illness were the problem; rather, he
saw in them that they had faith in him.

00:12:23.583 --> 00:12:28.500
That’s why they address him:
“Teacher.” And we too should

00:12:28.500 --> 00:12:30.959
always have that same attitude.

00:12:30.959 --> 00:12:36.368
We come before our Teacher and
allow ourselves to be shaped.

00:12:36.368 --> 00:12:40.302
That Teacher will bless me and change me.

00:12:40.902 --> 00:12:46.425
However, we can see it in
what follows in this Gospel.

00:12:46.425 --> 00:12:52.953
OK, he takes up this attitude: “Teacher.”
I’ve just mentioned Jesus’ path. He’s

00:12:52.953 --> 00:12:55.463
leaving Jericho—where is he going?

00:12:55.463 --> 00:13:01.489
Jesus is heading for Jerusalem,
and we know what awaits him there:

00:13:01.489 --> 00:13:06.510
the triumphant entry, then he’ll
be arrested, then imprisoned, then

00:13:06.510 --> 00:13:13.038
killed; and in the end Jesus will
rise again and ascend into heaven.

00:13:14.078 --> 00:13:19.546
In other words, you take up the stance
of a disciple: you no longer choose

00:13:19.546 --> 00:13:22.097
your own path, but follow the Lord.

00:13:22.097 --> 00:13:27.201
And the Lord said: “All those who
follow me, who are my disciples, will

00:13:27.201 --> 00:13:32.304
have to go through something similar.”
Where do we see that this blind man

00:13:32.304 --> 00:13:36.679
truly received spiritual sight? In
this: not only physically, but in the

00:13:36.679 --> 00:13:41.418
fact that he became Jesus’ disciple
and set off after Jesus to Jerusalem.

00:13:43.198 --> 00:13:48.024
Nowhere does it say there that he
went back to look for his cloak.

00:13:48.024 --> 00:13:52.161
It doesn’t say that anywhere; it
says he left everything and set

00:13:52.161 --> 00:13:53.884
off after Jesus, following Jesus.

00:13:53.884 --> 00:13:57.676
I was explaining this posture
of sitting and then getting up.

00:13:57.676 --> 00:13:59.745
Who else does Jesus come to?

00:13:59.745 --> 00:14:04.571
He’s sitting, it says, in the tax
booth, and Jesus says to him, “Come,

00:14:04.571 --> 00:14:09.398
follow me.” Jesus offers every one
of us the chance to go with him.

00:14:10.938 --> 00:14:13.684
However, we often grope about in the dark.

00:14:13.684 --> 00:14:18.490
We say we belong to Jesus, yet
we walk like geese in the fog.

00:14:18.490 --> 00:14:22.266
So often we’re lost, and
still we say we’re Jesus’ own.

00:14:22.266 --> 00:14:26.386
If Jesus is shining in our
hearts, we cannot lose our way.

00:14:26.386 --> 00:14:31.878
And even if we go through what the Lord
himself went through, we know that in

00:14:31.878 --> 00:14:34.282
the end the outcome is the Resurrection.

00:14:34.282 --> 00:14:40.118
Let them crucify us, let them hate us,
let them spit on us and call us names.

00:14:40.938 --> 00:14:45.362
This is what Jesus asks of
his disciples: to follow him.

00:14:45.362 --> 00:14:50.592
And I’m sure that in this church
Jesus won’t send any of us

00:14:50.592 --> 00:14:53.005
down a road we can’t endure.

00:14:53.005 --> 00:15:00.246
Jesus hasn’t put any of us on the path
we’re on right now if we can’t bear it.

00:15:00.246 --> 00:15:07.084
Be a disciple right where you are, on the
road you’re on, and let him shape you.

00:15:08.425 --> 00:15:13.543
And you see, I’ve just said it:
sometimes we’re spiritually blind.

00:15:13.543 --> 00:15:20.522
Yet God is so good, he blesses us
so much, life can be so beautiful

00:15:20.522 --> 00:15:26.106
at times, and we see nothing because
we’re blind, because we’re blind.

00:15:26.106 --> 00:15:32.155
Maybe we can see physically, but
spiritually we don’t see anything at all.

00:15:32.155 --> 00:15:37.273
Brother and sister, we’re blind
when we say we’re not capable

00:15:37.273 --> 00:15:40.064
of a relationship with the Lord.

00:15:40.745 --> 00:15:45.532
Brothers and sisters, we are blind
when we say there is no good.

00:15:45.532 --> 00:15:51.055
Brothers and sisters, we are blind when
we say that God doesn’t care about me.

00:15:51.055 --> 00:15:55.842
Brothers and sisters, we are blind
when we say God can’t forgive me.

00:15:55.842 --> 00:16:00.629
And how often we are that blind,
because we don’t see the good.

00:16:00.629 --> 00:16:05.785
Brothers and sisters, we are blind because
sometimes we follow evil, we don’t see.

00:16:07.064 --> 00:16:11.935
And that’s why sometimes we need,
like Bartimaeus, to leap up and

00:16:11.935 --> 00:16:17.211
cry out: “Jesus, Son of David,
have mercy on me!” He is blind.

00:16:17.211 --> 00:16:22.487
He gets up and goes towards
Jesus, but the Gospel says he ran.

00:16:22.487 --> 00:16:26.951
A blind man, believing he would
reach Jesus, must have fallen

00:16:26.951 --> 00:16:29.792
many times before he got to him.

00:16:29.792 --> 00:16:31.416
He took the risk.

00:16:31.416 --> 00:16:37.910
How many times do we get up and fall
too, but don’t stay on the ground.

00:16:37.940 --> 00:16:43.688
If, as a blind man, he ran towards Jesus
to meet him, I believe he must have

00:16:43.688 --> 00:16:46.394
fallen as he made his way to Jesus.

00:16:46.394 --> 00:16:49.775
How many times do we
set off and then fall?

00:16:49.775 --> 00:16:52.819
Get up and go again—seek
Jesus whenever you fall.

00:16:52.819 --> 00:16:54.848
Don’t stay down when you fall.

00:16:54.848 --> 00:16:57.553
Maybe Jesus is standing a metre from you.

00:16:57.553 --> 00:17:00.935
Maybe he’s that close, but
everything is darkened for you.

00:17:00.935 --> 00:17:04.317
Some people are so blind they
can’t see God’s providence,

00:17:04.317 --> 00:17:05.670
his certainty, his protection.

00:17:06.690 --> 00:17:11.876
Sometimes we’re so close to
God, and yet we don’t see Him.

00:17:11.876 --> 00:17:17.926
We don’t see Him in the sacraments,
we don’t see Him present in life,

00:17:17.926 --> 00:17:20.952
in our days as they pass by.

00:17:20.952 --> 00:17:25.274
Have we seen Him anywhere
today, even if only nearby?

00:17:25.274 --> 00:17:31.324
Sometimes we’re so blind we don’t see,
because we haven’t cast off the burden

00:17:31.324 --> 00:17:34.782
of false belief, that cloak that’s on us.

00:17:34.782 --> 00:17:41.697
That’s why God’s word today calls us to be
like Bartimaeus: to open ourselves to God,

00:17:41.697 --> 00:17:49.044
to see again, to shout out, to cry out,
so that the Lord can then strip everything

00:17:49.044 --> 00:17:52.070
from us and we can become disciples.

00:17:52.610 --> 00:17:55.527
Disciples who listen to the Lord.

00:17:55.527 --> 00:17:58.445
It isn’t always easy, I know.

00:17:58.445 --> 00:18:03.794
It’s not easy to strip off
everything that holds us back.

00:18:03.794 --> 00:18:10.602
Only if we truly want to, personally—just
think how much we’ve built up this

00:18:10.602 --> 00:18:15.465
tangled cloak of false beliefs
we carry about ourselves: about

00:18:15.465 --> 00:18:19.842
our own worth, our appearance,
our behaviour, our personality.

00:18:19.842 --> 00:18:26.650
And the same with God, because in that
way Satan steals everything from us.

00:18:28.446 --> 00:18:31.241
He’s happy for us to remain blind.

00:18:31.241 --> 00:18:36.433
The consequence of sin is that it
distorts our image of God, that

00:18:36.433 --> 00:18:38.830
we become blind and see nothing.

00:18:38.830 --> 00:18:44.820
So even if we’re spiritually blind, that
isn’t the problem: the Lord will heal us.

00:18:44.820 --> 00:18:47.217
We just need to cry out.

00:18:47.217 --> 00:18:50.811
We just need to notice that we’re in need.

00:18:50.811 --> 00:18:54.406
We just need to say it honestly to Jesus.

00:18:55.086 --> 00:19:00.092
If he had mercy on Mary Magdalene,
if he healed Bartimaeus, why

00:19:00.092 --> 00:19:03.012
wouldn’t the Lord touch you and me?

00:19:03.012 --> 00:19:06.349
Why are we afraid of God touching us?

00:19:06.349 --> 00:19:10.104
I know it’s sometimes hard
to listen to everything.

00:19:10.104 --> 00:19:15.110
I know it’s sometimes hard to do
everything, but the most beautiful

00:19:15.110 --> 00:19:22.202
thing you can do is to let God love
you, to let the Lord love your wounds

00:19:22.202 --> 00:19:24.706
and mine, because God’s love heals.

00:19:25.706 --> 00:19:30.426
That’s it — that’s the
light that opens our eyes.

00:19:30.426 --> 00:19:36.720
That’s the light that gives
us the grace for the Lord to

00:19:36.720 --> 00:19:39.866
shape us, to change our hearts.

00:19:39.866 --> 00:19:47.209
Maybe, in life, we’ve so many times
placed our hearts in the wrong hands.

00:19:47.209 --> 00:19:51.405
So many times our emotions have been used.

00:19:51.405 --> 00:19:55.076
So many times we’ve been
spiritually infected.

00:19:55.076 --> 00:20:00.846
So many times we may have carried
something traumatic within us.

00:20:01.886 --> 00:20:04.970
Maybe life – our
childhood – has shaped us.

00:20:04.970 --> 00:20:11.578
All of that is like a cloak of
life we all carry on our backs.

00:20:11.578 --> 00:20:12.900
All of us.

00:20:12.900 --> 00:20:14.222
You’re only human.

00:20:14.222 --> 00:20:19.068
That’s why a person needs God,
needs His closeness, and shouldn’t

00:20:19.068 --> 00:20:21.271
be afraid – afraid to click.

00:20:21.271 --> 00:20:27.439
I think no one has the right to
complain about life, about God, about

00:20:27.439 --> 00:20:32.286
everything that’s happening to them,
if they haven’t cried out sincerely.

00:20:33.306 --> 00:20:37.663
Because there’s one thing I keep noticing
about people: they’re always moaning,

00:20:37.663 --> 00:20:39.842
but they’ve never truly cried out.

00:20:39.842 --> 00:20:42.384
They’ve never genuinely
screamed from the heart.

00:20:42.384 --> 00:20:46.378
So does God really want us to
torment ourselves like that?

00:20:46.378 --> 00:20:50.372
Does God really care that
your life and mine fall apart?

00:20:50.372 --> 00:20:56.546
Does God really want chaos to rule in my
life and yours, in your family and mine?

00:20:56.846 --> 00:20:57.345
No.

00:20:57.345 --> 00:20:59.341
It matters to Satan.

00:20:59.341 --> 00:21:02.834
So why don’t we cry out sincerely?

00:21:02.834 --> 00:21:06.827
Why don’t we talk it through with Jesus?

00:21:06.827 --> 00:21:09.322
About the state we’re in.

00:21:09.322 --> 00:21:14.812
Bartimaeus realised what condition
he was in: I’m ill, I’m blind.

00:21:14.812 --> 00:21:18.804
Do we believers realise
what state we’re in?

00:21:18.804 --> 00:21:21.798
I’ve got the feeling some don’t.

00:21:21.798 --> 00:21:28.286
Some people come, they talk and
talk and talk, but they say nothing

00:21:28.286 --> 00:21:33.277
about themselves and they don’t
see their own condition — and

00:21:33.277 --> 00:21:39.266
it’s very chaotic, very alarming,
very bad — but they don’t see it.

00:21:41.853 --> 00:21:47.247
And that’s where we need to ask the Lord
to open our eyes, so that we can cry

00:21:47.247 --> 00:21:52.640
out for the Lord to set us free from it;
to stop being people who only moan, and

00:21:52.640 --> 00:21:57.434
instead bring it to Jesus, hand it over
to Jesus, and cry out to Jesus sincerely.

00:21:58.133 --> 00:22:03.339
Perhaps that’s why we don’t cry out
— because we’re afraid we’d have to become

00:22:03.339 --> 00:22:08.545
his disciples, that we wouldn’t be
able to go wherever we want any more.

00:22:08.545 --> 00:22:13.750
Believe me, there are some who won’t open
their hearts to Jesus, won’t surrender

00:22:13.750 --> 00:22:18.584
their lives completely, because we all
know from experience: if you’re open to

00:22:18.584 --> 00:22:24.533
God’s grace and to the Holy Spirit, then
you’re no longer the one making the plans.

00:22:25.293 --> 00:22:31.567
Then God leads you, and it’s like what
they said to Saint Pe–Peter: “And now

00:22:31.567 --> 00:22:37.003
someone else will fasten your belt.”
So yes, that’s where the adventure with

00:22:37.003 --> 00:22:42.440
God begins: that God makes you a joyful
person, that you see—really see—beauty,

00:22:42.440 --> 00:22:48.713
that you see life, that you breathe in
life, instead of walking around as if

00:22:48.713 --> 00:22:54.986
we’re just getting through the days,
as if life is so heavy that we can

00:22:54.986 --> 00:22:57.914
hardly wait just to survive the day.

00:22:58.393 --> 00:23:02.145
And I think that’s how I
feel right now, being in the

00:23:02.145 --> 00:23:03.708
middle of organising all this.

00:23:03.708 --> 00:23:05.583
But it’ll pass, it’ll all pass.

00:23:05.583 --> 00:23:09.022
What matters is throwing
yourself into the arms of God the

00:23:09.022 --> 00:23:10.897
Father and letting God lead us.

00:23:10.897 --> 00:23:14.648
Look, ahead of us we’ve got adoration,
we’ve got prayer, Holy Mass.

00:23:14.648 --> 00:23:16.211
Just delight in God, rest.

00:23:16.211 --> 00:23:19.650
In this moment, switch off from
everything; take off your cloak,

00:23:19.650 --> 00:23:23.714
take it off, and leave it down
there in front of the church.

00:23:24.053 --> 00:23:28.161
Down there in front of the church there
are people keeping an eye on everything.

00:23:28.161 --> 00:23:30.077
No one’s going to take your coat.

00:23:30.077 --> 00:23:31.172
So, just be brave.

00:23:31.274 --> 00:23:32.573
Amen.

